      <body>
         <entry xml:id="pargod-dlgenr"
            type="mainEntry"
            xml:lang="en"
            prev="#privatiyyot-dlgenr"
            next="#pargod-ys"
            source="Genesis Rabbah">
            <form type="lemma">
               <orth type="lemma" xml:lang="jpa" opt="false" select="true">פרגוד</orth>
               <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb" opt="false">prgwd</orth>
               <pron notation="rabbinic">pargod</pron>
               <gramGrp>
                  <gram type="pos">noun</gram>
                  <gram type="gen">m.</gram>
               </gramGrp>
               <form type="inflected">
                  <orth type="inflected" xml:lang="jpa">פרגודין</orth>
                  <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb">prgwdyn</orth>
                  <pron notation="rabbinic">pargoudin</pron>
                  <gramGrp>
                     <gram type="num">pl.</gram>
                  </gramGrp>
               </form>
            </form>
            <sense xml:id="pargod-dlgenr-1">
               <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en" subtype="sense">
                  <quote>bordered garment</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="translationEquivalent" xml:lang="grc">
                  <quote>παραγαύδιον</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="translationEquivalent" xml:lang="la">
                  <quote>paragauda</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example" xml:lang="jpa">
                  <quote>ויפשיטו את יוסף, זה הפינס, את כתנתו זה חלוק, את כתנת הפסים זה הפרגוד, אשר עליו זה פמלניא</quote>
                  <bibl>
                     <ref type="witness">84,16</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">II 1019: 5</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <ref type="entry" xml:lang="jpa">פמלניא</ref>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>And they stripped Joseph [Gen 37,23] – that refers to his cloak; his coat, to his shirt; the coat of many colours – the bordered garment; that was on him – his breeches. (Cf. Freedman / Simon II 781)</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <note>= <bibl type="ancient">Yalq 142 [II 725: 9]</bibl></note>
               </cit>
            </sense>
            <note>The word is probably of Pers. origin. Cf. <ref type="entry" xml:lang="jpa" target="pargod-ys.html">פרגוד</ref> Yalq (with a second sense).</note>
            <ref type="bibliography">
               <bibl>
                  <title>Sokoloff, DJPA</title>
                  <citedRange>409b</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl>
                  <title>Heijmanns</title>
                  <citedRange>177</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl>
                  <title>Krauss, LW II</title>
                  <citedRange>477b</citedRange>
               </bibl>
            </ref>
         </entry>
